\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Supposing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{k}$
\end_inset

 can be written as a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{v}_{k-1}$
\end_inset

, we have immediately that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{v}_{p}$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{v}_{p}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}\neq\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 are linearly dependent.
 Then there exists a linear combination 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+a_{p}\mathbf{v}_{p}=\mathbf{0}.
\]

\end_inset

It must be that at least one of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2},a_{3},\ldots,a_{p}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}\neq\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\max\{i:a_{i}\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $k>1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\neq0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+a_{k}\mathbf{v}_{k}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}_{k}=-\frac{a_{1}}{a_{k}}\mathbf{v}_{1}-\frac{a_{2}}{a_{k}}\mathbf{v}_{2}-\cdots-\frac{a_{k-1}}{a_{k}}\mathbf{v}_{k-1}.
\]

